Class Default

  • java.lang.Object
    • model.gameoflife.algorithms.Default
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Algorithm

    public class Default
extends java.lang.Object
implements Algorithm
    This is the default implementation of Conway S23/B3 Game Of Life rules and it implements the Algorithm interface

      • update

        public void update()
        This method checks if we need to expand the game board and runs countNeighbours(int, int), nextGeneration(int, int) which is our algorithm. Lastly it clears the neighbour array using clearNeighbours(int, int)
        Specified by:
        update in interface Algorithm

      • updateConcurrent

        public void updateConcurrent(int start,
                             int stop,
                             int clearStart,
                             int clearStop,
                             java.util.concurrent.CyclicBarrier barrier)
        This is the concurrent version of our algorithm and each thread will call this method and run the algorithm on a specified segment of the game board. The CyclicBarrier synchronizes the threads and makes them wait before calling the nextGeneration(int, int) method. We also use CyclicBarrier to prevent synchronizing problems when clearing the neighbour array in the clearNeighbours(int, int) method
        Specified by:
        updateConcurrent in interface Algorithm
        Parameters:
        start - The start position of the segment
        stop - The end position of the segment
        clearStart - The start of the clear neighbours method
        clearStop - The end of the clear neighbours method
        barrier - The CyclicBarrier to use in the algorithm

      • countNeighbours

        private void countNeighbours(int start,
                             int stop)
        This is a synchronized method that counts cells that are alive within a segment. The access to updateNeighbours(int, int) is restricted so that we don't get problems with threads interfering with each other
        Parameters:
        start - Start of the segment
        stop - The end of the segment
        See Also:
        Thread
